column23: We began the year with fairly nice furniture (after having to wait for it to arrive for a few days). Then, they replaced the couch with a very uncomfortable couch that is very unlike the one pictured on the Cuicicalli website and online digital tour. Me and my roommates were very unhappy with this, but we didn't say anything. Then, we got a notice that they were trading out our dining table chairs. When we received our new dining chairs, we were very disappointed. Again, these were very uncomfortable chairs made of hard plastic. Again, very different from the chairs online being displayed as amenities for this residence hall. I and all of my roommates, as well as other people in Cuic have discussed our immense displeasure and anger over the new furniture, especially the dining chairs. I believe it is unfair to be shown that we would be getting comfortable furniture online, only to reveal that we would be living with very uncomfortable furniture, especially given the rent rates that we pay. I pay almost the same rent as my friends in full apartments, and those include kitchens, and real, livable furniture. I am very disappointed with the decision to take away our furniture and replace it with the practically unusable furniture we are now living with. We are forced to live on campus for two years, yet we are being denied basic living amenities such as a kitchen, and comfortable couches and dining chairs.

So here I am paying nearly the same amount (give or take 100$) as someone living off campus, yet I am forced to live and pay for a room that has far worse living conditions. The financial¬†aid office is more helpful in resolving any issues I might have (even after waiting 3 hrs on zoom) than the housing office. In conclusion, if I could find a way to attend SDSU and not live on campus, it would have already been done by now. I have thought of transferring multiple times purely because of housing.¬†
